Double  helical  DNA  is  super  coiled  for  proper  packaging  inside  the  cell.  The  replication  machinery needs enzymes to perform the tasks of uncoiling and unwinding the DNA before the  replication fork. These topological problems are solved through enzymes called topoisomerases.  The topoisomerases were discovered by James Wang in 1970, when he identified topoisomerase  I in Escherichia coli. According to James Wang, “DNA topoisomerases are the magicians of the  DNA  world.  By  allowing  DNA  strands  or  double  helices  to  pass  through  each  other,  they  can  solve  all  of  the  topological  problems  of  DNA  in  replication,  transcription  and  other  cellular  transactions”  [1].  Topoisomerase  binds  to  the  DNA  and  removes  the  torsion  produced  due  to  over-winding  by  cutting  either  a  single  strand  or  the  double  strand  at  the  phosphate  backbone  linkage (Figure 1A-C). Though these breaks at several points, topoisomerase helps in untangling  the DNA, which resealed later utilizing ATP. The main function of topoisomerases is unlinking  the  DNA  by  making  several  transient  cuts  inside  through  a  conserved  tyrosine  amino  acid  residue at the catalytic position of the functional enzyme. Abstract: The inhibition of pathogenic bacteria at the replication stage is important to halt their  further  reproduction  and  spread.  The  replication  enzymes  include  the  DNA  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  that  are  recognized  targets  for  the  infection  control.  Novel  antibiotic  compounds  are  always  in  demand  for  targeting  different  active  sites  of  these  enzymes.  Although  quinolones  are  the  current  drug  of  choice  for  targeting  these  enzymes,  emerging  resistance  is  a  global  concern.  Wide-scale  efforts  are  needed  to  overcome  the  emerging  resistance by designing more potent drugs. In this article, we have reviewed the last five years  progress of various classes of non-quinolone-based chemical compounds that are tested for their  antibacterial activities.  Keywords: bacterial gyrase; topoisomerase IV; drug resistance; binding sites; potency.  topoisomerase enzymes that are important drug targets in pathogenic bacteria and human cancer  cells. Based on the single and double strand transient cuts, the topoisomerases can be classified  as type I and type II [2–4]. The two types of topoisomerases are structurally and mechanistically  distinct  from  one  another  [2,3].  Bacteria  have  two  structurally  similar  type  II  topoisomerases,  called gyrase and topoisomerase IV [5–9]. These two enzymes contain heterotetrameric subunits  [6–9]. The gyrase has two copies of each GyrA and GyrB subunits while topoisomerase IV has  two copies each of ParC and ParE subunits [6–9].   Quinolone  based  antibiotics  are  suitable

the  bacterial  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  because  of  selective  toxicity  [9–12].  However,  mutations  in  the  quinolone  binding  site  of  gyrase  or  topoisomerase  IV  (gyrA  or  parC  gene)  results  in  resistance  to  quinolones [12]. The mutations mostly occur near the tyrosine residue (Tyr122 for GyrA, Tyr120  for ParC) of the catalytic site [13,14]. These domains (GyrA or ParC) are called the quinolone  resistance  determining  regions  (QRDR)  [15].  In  the  E.  coli  GyrA  subunit,  Ser83  and  Asp87  while  Ser80  and  Glu84  are  mostly  mutated  in  ParC  subunit  [13,14,16].  The  result  of  mutation  leads  to  poor  binding  of  quinolone  to  the  enzyme.  A  mutation  in  the  serine  residue  results  in  lower binding affinity between the quinolone and the enzyme while  mutation of acidic residue  has a much stronger effect on the binding affinities (Figure 1D) [6,17,18].

As compared to GyrA and ParC, mutations in GyrB and ParE are less common. In cases of  E. coli mutation in Asp426 and Lys447 of GyrB, and Leu445 of ParE, resulted in drug resistance  [12,19].  Mutation  in  both  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  causes  increased  level  of  resistance  to  quinolones [6,17,18]. There are several pathogenic bacteria in which there is only gyrase, while  the  topoisomerase  IV  is  absent  [4–6].  These  bacteria  include  Mycobacterium  tuberculosis,  Helicobacter  pylori,  and  Treponema  pallidum,  and  explains  why  resistance  to  quinolones  is  frequently  observed  in  them  [12].  It  is  also  believed  that  the  QRDR  mutation  site  is  the  sole  cause of quinolone resistance, as the water–metal bridge is disrupted in the quinolone interaction  site [6,14]. Development of potent alternate inhibitors of bacterial gyrase and topoisomerase IV  are  highly  demanded  due  to  the  current  resistance  threat  by  multi-drug  resistant  strains  of  bacteria  [20–22].  Such  efforts  produced  several  compounds  at  the  laboratory  stage  and  are  termed as novel bacterial topoisomerase inhibitors (NBTIs) [20].   1.1 Novel Bacterial Topoisomerase Inhibitors (NBTIs)  These NBTIs bind mostly to alternative sites to the quinolone binding site in topoisomerase IV  and DNA gyrase of bacteria [25]. There are two classes of NBTIs.    1.1.1  Type I NBTIs

The common type I NBTIs include gepotidacin and its related analogues that are in clinical trials  (Figure  2)  [26].  Gepotidacin  is  a  triazaacenaphthylene  that  is  a  type  II  topoisomerase  inhibitor  [26–28]. It strongly inhibits the Neisseria gonorrhoeae and other conventional pathogens grown  in low microgram concentration [26–28]. Miles et al. prepared a series of analogues of tricyclics  called GSK945237 (Figure 1 and 2a), and most of them possess a broad spectrum of antibacterial  [23].  They  also  demonstrate  good  activity  against  different  pathogenic  bacteria  pharmacokinetics,  and  related  compounds  of  triazaacenaphthylene  cause  cardiac  related  toxicity  as  they  act  as  human  ether  related  gene  (hERG)  inhibition  [29–32].  Some  of  the  compounds  were  modified  to  minimize  the  hERG  toxicity and contain a broad spectrum of antibacterial activity. Among these, AM-8722 (Figure  2)  showed  favorable  pharmacokinetic  qualities  and  was  efﬁcacious  in  murine  species  having  bacterial septicemia [31]. Further, the 1,5-naphthyridine oxabicyclooctane linked NBTIs do not  exhibit cross-resistance to other known antibiotics and have the capacity to destroy drug resistant  pathogenic bacteria [29–31]. The structural studies showed that these NBTIs bind to the interface  of  gyrase  in  complex  with  the  DNA  before  the  cleavage  state  [29,33].  The  complex  of  NBTIs/gyrase/DNA is stabilized by a polar interaction of an Asp83 side chain [29,33].

Li  et  al.  used  nuclear  magnetic  resonance  (NMR)  spectroscopy  to  study  the  drug–protein  interaction  of  the  topoisomerase  IV  enzyme  of  E.  coli  [34].  The  ParE  subunit  of  the  topoisomerase IV enzyme contains the ATP binding pocket, and for improving drug efficacy, it  is  important  to  understand  the  drug–protein  interaction  [34].  In  this  spectroscopic  data,  they  reported the protein backbone assignment for the N-terminal domain of E. coli ParE subunit. The  obtained  secondary  structural  information  and  the  assignment  will  help  in  structure-based  antibacterial compound development that will help in targeting the ParE subunit of the enzyme  Figure  2. In  the  last  few  years,  the  work  on  drug  development  against  bacterial  gyrase  and  topoisomerases,  and  their  resistance  to  these  drugs  by  different  bacteria  have  expanded  enormously,  creating  a  need  to  review  this  work.  Some  reviews  were  published  in  2016  [36],  which showed novelty, and a critical analysis of this work is essential for better understanding of  chemotherapy. Nagaraja et al. reviewed the current therapeutic agents for curing tuberculosis by  targeting  DNA  gyrase and topoisomerase  I enzymes from  M. tuberculosis [37].  In this review,  the  authors  pointed  out  that  the  topoisomerase  enzyme  of  M.  tuberculosis  should  be  targeted  along with its gyrase [37].

Malik et al. found a new binding mode for quinolones inside the gyrase and topoisomerase  [38].  In  this  new  mode,  the  attached  group  at  carbon-7  of  the  quinolone  ring  (ciprofloxacin)  interacts  with  the  topoisomerase  [38].  The  positional  substituents  are  useful  to  overcome  the  resistance  offered  by  bacteria  through  mutation  in  the  binding  pocket  of  DNA  gyrase  and  topoisomerases  [38].  It  was  observed  that  the  attachment  of  a  dinitrophenyl  group  at  the  C-7  position  of  ciprofloxacin  resulted  in  a  decrease  in  resistance  offered  by  E.  coli  [38,39].  This  study may be helpful in designing novel C-7 analogues of quinolones and other classes of drugs  that target the gyrase and topoisomerase of resistant pathogenic bacteria.

There  are  several  compounds  which  are  placed  in  class  II  NBTIs  by  Tse-Dinh.  These  include  a  quinolone  pyrimidone  trione-1  (QPT-1)  and  a  spiropyrimidinetrone  based  compound  called  Zoliflodacin  (AZD0914)  [20].  QPT-1  attaches  to  the  same  site  as  moxifloxacin  to  the  bacterial  gyrase  but  is  not  linked  through  the  water–metal  bridge  [40].  The  barbituric  acid  of  QPT-1 exists in several keto-enol tautomeric forms in the binding site, and makes the most of the  interactions  with  the  bacterial  gyrase  Asp-437  and  DNA  [40].  However,  one  characteristic  of  QPT-1 is similar to moxifloxacin, in that QPT-1 inhibits the bacterial topoisomerase-IV/gyrase  after the DNA cleavage [40]. The AZD0914 showed that some structural similarities to QPT-1,  such as the presence of barbituric acid in its structure and a few other rings.

Zoliflodacin  (AZD0914  )  has  been  more  selective  for  inhibition  of  N.  gonorrhea  and  less  toxic for human topoisomerases [41,42]. The clinical trials and laboratory research is ongoing on  AZD0914  for  that  spiropyrimidinetrione,  acts  as  a  DNA  gyrase/topoisomerase  inhibitor  [43].  This  compound  stabilizes the protein  cleaved DNA  covalent adduct (gyrase/topoisomerase cleaved DNA)  [43].  They tested the spiropyrimidinetrione on approximately 187 isolates of N. gonorrhoeae collected  from  Nanjing,  China  [43].  These  isolates  were  resistant  to  different  drugs  including  ciprofloxacin, azithromycin, tetracycline, and ceftriaxone in different concentrations. The reason  that such isolates of N. gonorrhoeae can be controlled with this novel spiropyrimidinetrione may  be due to their first ever exposure to this drug.        Simocyclinone and its analogues are another group of class II NBTIs. The simocyclinone can  be obtained from Streptomyces antibioticus Tu6040 and other strains of streptomyces [39,44,45].  Its structure contains four distinct chemical groups. These include an angucyclic polyketide core  group, a deoxyhexose sugar, a tetraene as a side chain in its molecule, and a halogenated amino- coumarin moiety, as shown in Figure 3 [39,44,45]. There are several analogues of simocyclinone  that  mainly  differ  in  the  presence  or  absence  of  the  keto  groups  or  its  tautomerization  in  the  angucyclic  polyketide  core  group,  but  simocyclinone  D8  is  the  most  potent  against  bacterial  gyrase.  The  mode  of  action  of  simocyclone  D8  and  other  analogues  are  different  in  that  SD8

treatment  of  N.  gonorrhoea.  Recently,  Su  et  al.  reported  binds in a site other than that of fluoroquinones in the A-subunit of gyrase [46], while its flavone  group  analogues  intercalates  with  DNA  [47].  The  SD8  binds  with  the  N-terminal  region  of  bacterial gyrase and inhibits the early stages of the enzyme interaction with the DNA [41,43–45].  The flavone group analogue of SD8 are highly toxic to humans due to intercalation with human  DNA.  Few  other  analogues  of  this  group  are  less  toxic  for  humans,  thus  there  is  a  need  to  optimize  these  compounds  in  order  to  get  better  potency  against  bacteria,  and  non-toxicity  for  humans.  Surface  plasmon  resonance  studies  provided  the  initial  data  that  flavone  based  analogues of SD8 are not interacting with the gyrase enzyme and DNA unwinding assay proved  its intercalation with DNA [47].  The  isothiazolone  compound  REDX04957  (Figure  3)  and  its  two  enantiomer  forms,  REDX05967  and  REDX05990    have  been  tested  for  inhibitory  action  against  bacterial  type  II  topoisomerases  [51].  These  compounds  have  the  inhibitory  power  to  halt  the  supercoiling  function  of  wild-type  DNA  gyrase  enzymes  and  the  decatenation  functioning  of  the  topoisomerase  IV  enzyme. They are  active against the quinolone resistant bacterial strains that  possess  GyrA  S83L  and  D87G  mutations  [51].  In  another  study,  isothiazolone    was  tested  on

A series of isothiazolones were made based on the  SAR  methods  that  are  better  inhibitors  for  the  type  II  topoisomerase.  Most  of  the  derivatives  were  potent  drug  candidates  for  both  Gram-positive  and  Gram-negative  bacteria  that  are  multi  drug  resistant  (MDR)  [52,53].  Overall,  these  isothiazolone  compounds  exhibit  significant  inhibitory  action  against  both  Gram-positive  and  Gram-negative  bacteria,  showing  a  good  binding interaction with gyrase and type II topoisomerase.   Savage  et  al.  at  Redx  Pharma,  UK  tested  novel  tricyclic  topoisomerase  inhibitors,  which  they  named  as  REDX04139,  REDX05604  and  REDX05931  on  different  strains  of  pathogenic  Gram positive and Gram negative bacteria (Figure 4) [54]. These compounds have in vitro and in  vivo efficacy  [54].  In  another study REDX05931 was tested on the Gram-negative  bacteria,  N.  gonorrhoeae  that  causes  gonorrhea  in  humans  [55].  The  experimental  results  from  a  murine  model show that REDX05931 has high bioavailability, and this compound is effective for multi- resistant N. gonorrhoeae infection [55].

Sandhaus  et  al.  targeted  the  mycobacterium  species  topoisomerase  I  with  small  polyamine  scaffold molecules [56]. Among the newly designed and synthesized polyamines, (Figure 4) four  possessed  bactericidal  activities  against  the  M.  smegmatis  and  M.  tuberculosis  [56].  The  minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC’s) results showed that these small molecules inhibit the  growth  of  mycobacteria  that  have  overexpression  of  recombinant  topoisomerase  I.  The  E.  coli  growth was not affected by these compounds, and the researchers were of the view that it was  not taken up by these bacteria. These small polyamine molecules had  no affect because  the E.  coli contain topoisomerase III. In mycobacteria, topoisomerase I is the sole topoisomerase, hence  its  targeting  by  anti-topoisomerase  compounds.  These  tested  compounds  should  be  further  optimized  for  their  antitubercular  properties  through  structure  activity  relationship  (SAR)  studies. For understanding its mode action, it may be helpful to crystallize the topoisomerase I  structure with polyamine compounds. In this way, more selective and potent compounds can be  made in the future  Figure  4.  Some  of  the  tested  novel  tricyclic  topoisomerase  inhibitors  synthesized  by  Redx  Pharma,  UK  [54]  and  the  polyamine  molecules  that  are  active  against  mycobacteria [56].

Recently kibdelomycin (Figure 5), a natural product, was shown capable of inhibiting gyrase  and topoisomerase IV [57]. This antibiotic is active against a number of MDR bacteria from both  Gram-positive and Gram-negative groups [4]. The X-ray co-crystal structures of kibdelomycin in  complex with GyrB (PDB ID 4URM) and ParE (PDB ID 4URL) subunits showed a unique dual  arm of U-shaped multi-site binding never encountered with other gyrase inhibitors [57,58]. The  kibdelomycin  interacts  with  the  enzyme  through  a  number  of  hydrophobic  and  electrostatic  interactions [57]. The pyrrolamide part of kibdelomycin holds the ATP binding site of the GyrB  or  ParE  subunit,  while  the  dichloro  pyrrole  ring  is  hidden  in  the  hydrophobic  residues  [57].  Kibdelomycin is poised for preclinical development for C. difficile-related infections treatment,  and  most  importantly,  the  co-crystal  structures  of  kibdelomycin  provide  a  unique  insight  into  structure-guided  structure  modification.  This  could  lead  to  a  better  broader-spectrum  systemic  antibiotic, potentially covering many pathogens [57].

Thiosemicarbazide  derivatives  (Figure  5)  are  also  efficient  inhibitors  of  bacterial  topoisomerase  II  (Gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV)  [59–61].  They  can  inhibit  the  gyrase  of  S.  aureus with an IC50 of less than 15 µM (Table 1) [60,62]. These compounds also show potency  on other bacterial strains of Staphylococcus spp. and Enterococcus faecalis, as well as clinical S.  aureus isolates at non-cytotoxic level in mammalian cells [60]. Although the exact mechanism of  action of thiosemicarbazide is not yet clear but molecular docking studies predicted that it binds  to the ATP binding site of topoisomerase [59,60]. Thiosemicarbazide should be further explored,  not  only  for  bacterial  topoisomerase  inhibitors,  but  for  other  target  enzymes  because  of  the  sulfur, oxygen and nitrogen atoms in its structure that can can interact through hydrogen bonding  in the binding pockets of the receptor [63–65].             Recently, quinolone resistance has been observed in Ureaplasma spp., that are associated  with human genital parts [66]. A number of residues of the GyrA, GyrB, ParC and ParE subunits  of the proteins showed mutations. The point mutation in both subunits of bacterial DNA gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  is  a  common  phenomenon  [66].  The  DNA  GyrB  subunit  of  E.  coli  has  been  selected  as  a  target  for  carboxamide  analogues  and  it  was  observed  that  4,5,6,7- tetrahydrobenzo[1,2-d]thiazole-2,6-diamine  compounds  inhibit  it  in  the  lower  micro  molar  concentration  (Figure  5)  [67].  However,  these  compounds  were  not  effective  against  several  Gram-positive  and  Gram-negative  bacteria  [67].  It  may  be  better  to

The  GyrB  and  ParE  subunit  of  bacterial  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  perform  the  ATP  hydrolysis  function  during  decatenation  of  DNA  for  the  demand  of  free  energy  and  negative  supercoils  [71–73].  This  ATP  binding  site  of  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  is  a  suitable  drug  target for the control of resistant bacteria [74]. Due to the high sequence similarity of the GyrB  and  ParE,  they  can  be  targeted  with  the  same  drug  candidate  [74].  The  recent  X-ray  crystal  structure of S. aureus GyrB subunit (PDB ID 5D7D and 5D7R) with a small molecule inhibitor  in  its  active  site  provides  an  opportunity  to  develop  novel  inhibitors  [75].  In  the  past,  both  computational  methods  [76]  and  experimental  approaches  [77,78]  have  been  used  for  its  inhibition  using  novel  ligands.  The  proven  drugs  for  the  GyrB  and  ParE  subunit  ATPase  inhibitors  are  the  natural  antibiotic  novobiocin,  cyclothialidines  (Figure  5),  coumarins,  and  several  others  [69].  However,  resistance  to  these  available  drugs  is  also  increasing  due  to  fast  mutation in the ATP binding site of GyrB and ParE subunits of various bacterial strains [79,80].

Fragment-based  drug  discovery  (FBDD)  is  a  process  of  building  a  drug  from  small  fragments  that  initially  bind  weakly,  but  the  full  compound  resulted  in  a  high  affinity  for  the  target protein [81–85]. Mesleh et al. used the fragment-based screening (FBS) approach to search  suitable compounds that can bind in the ATP binding site of the GyrB subunit of S. aureus [70].  Through the NMR fragment-based screening method, they discovered several pyrazolopyridone  analogues that were suitable hits [70]. These hit compounds were further optimized, resulting in  an active analogue (Figure 5) with IC50 of 0.265 µM [70].           In another combination of fragment-based drug discovery and a computational approach of  molecular  docking  simulation,  Anderluh  et  al.  searched  for  novel  chemical  linker  groups  that  interact in the active site of the DNA gyrase B subunit [68]. The search showed that piperidin-4- yl  and  4-cyclohexyl  pyrrole-2carboxamides  interact  favorably  in  the  active  site  [68].  They  synthesized  the  desired  library  of  compounds  and  testecd  them  on  E.  coli  and  S.  aureus  DNA  trans-4-(4,5-dibromo1H-pyrrole-2- GyrB  carboxamide)cyclohexyl)glycine having IC50 of 16 µM potency and 4-(4-(3,4-dichloro-5-methyl- 1H-pyrrole-2carboxamido)piperidin-1-yl)-4-oxobutanoic acid (Figure 5) with an IC50 of 0.5 µM  against E. coli [68].      The  fragment-based  drug  design  approach  showed  that  pyrazolopyridones  are  also  suitable  inhibitors  for  the  GyrB  ATPase  activity  [86]. -based  drug  design  approach  showed  that  pyrazolopyridones  are  also  suitable  inhibitors  for  the  GyrB  ATPase  activity  [86].  Optimization  of  pyrazolopyridones  provided  an  analogue that possesses an IC50 of 0.27 µM for S. aureus GyrB (Figure 5 and Table 1) [86]. The  development of novel compounds through fragment and structure based approaches should also  be evaluated for their selective toxicity so that efforts for making potent drugs can be expedited  [86]. Chen et al. used the fragment based approach for targeting the E. coli GyrB subunit using  differential  scanning  fluorimetry  (DSF)  technique  for  screening  the  potential  fragments  [87].  They  started  their  initial  screening  by  taking  novobiocin  (Figure  5)  as  a  selected  ligand  [87].  They screened a total of 1800 fragments, out of which 14 fragments have the potential to interact  favorably with GyrB subunit [87]. In the final stage they choose a fragment that was built into a  new  group  of  effective  phenyl  pyrazole  inhibitors  [87]. Conclusions and Future Perspectives  Targeting  bacterial  DNA  gyrase/topoisomerase  IV  is  important  for  the  selective  toxicity  against pathogenic bacteria. The development of non-quinolone-based compounds are necessary  as the threat of multi-resistant drug pathogens are increasing due to the overuse of the available  antibiotics  and  frequent  mutations  in  the  targeted  enzymes.  For  this  purpose,  non-quinolone- based  inhibitors  should  be  developed  that  can  target  various  active  sites  in  the  bacterial  DNA  gyrase  and  topoisomerase  IV  enzyme.  In  this  way  a  pool  of  new  potent  antibiotics  will  be  available  for  the  treatment  of  different  infectious  diseases.  On  one  side  the  efforts  shoud  be  expedited for the search of novel antibiotcis from bacterial and fungal sources and on the other  side the available drugs should be modified in such a way that the chances of resistance to them  is lower and they have more potency. The computational chemistry approaches should be fully  utilized, as libraries of millions of compounds are available online in different repositories that  can  provide  specific  inhibitors  for  the  various  sites  of  the  GyrB  and  ParE  subunits  of  DNA  gyrase and topoisomerase IV of different bacteria.
